items.name: Sophie Gengembre Anderson Style
items.description:
Sophie Gengembre Anderson (1823-1903) was a British-born artist known for her romantic and sentimental paintings, particularly her depictions of women and children. She was one of the few successful female artists of her time and played a significant role in challenging the gender barriers in the art world.

Anderson's style was characterized by its softness, delicate brushwork, and attention to detail. Her paintings often featured idyllic scenes of rural life, enchanting landscapes, and portraits of women and children engaged in everyday activities. She had a remarkable ability to capture the innocence, tenderness, and emotional depth of her subjects.

Her works were influenced by the Pre-Raphaelite movement, with their emphasis on vibrant colors, intricate patterns, and a return to detailed realism. Anderson's paintings often evoked a sense of tranquility and nostalgia, appealing to the sentimentality of Victorian audiences.

Throughout her career, Anderson achieved significant success and received critical acclaim for her art. Her works were exhibited at prestigious venues, including the Royal Academy of Arts in London. She gained popularity not only in Britain but also in the United States, where she eventually settled and continued to paint.

Anderson's legacy as a female artist who achieved recognition and success during a time when opportunities for women in the arts were limited is remarkable. Her ability to evoke emotions through her portrayals of women and children, combined with her technical skill, has left a lasting impact on the art world.

Sophie Gengembre Anderson's paintings continue to captivate audiences with their beauty, sentimentality, and timeless appeal. Her contributions to the art world, both as a skilled artist and as a trailblazer for female artists, remain celebrated and respected to this day.

items.name: Stained Glass Portrait
items.description:
A stained glass portrait is a work of art created using colored glass pieces assembled together to form a representation of a person or subject. This art form has a rich history dating back centuries and is known for its exquisite beauty and the play of light that filters through the glass.

Stained glass portraits often employ the technique of leaded glass, where individual glass pieces are cut, shaped, and fitted into a framework of lead or other metals. The glass pieces are carefully selected for their colors, textures, and opacity, allowing the artist to create a captivating image with depth and dimension.

The artist begins by creating a design or pattern for the portrait, carefully considering the subject's features, expressions, and overall composition. The glass pieces are then cut and shaped according to the design, and the lead framework is constructed to hold the glass pieces together. Once assembled, the portrait is often strengthened with soldering and reinforced with additional support.

The true beauty of a stained glass portrait lies in its ability to transform when illuminated by natural or artificial light. The colors come alive, casting vibrant hues and creating a mesmerizing effect as the light passes through the glass. The interplay of light and shadow enhances the details and contours of the portrait, evoking a sense of awe and wonder.

Stained glass portraits can be found in various settings, such as religious buildings, museums, and private residences. They are often revered for their intricate craftsmanship, artistic expression, and their ability to create a serene and contemplative atmosphere.

Creating a stained glass portrait requires not only technical skill but also a deep understanding of color, light, and form. Artists who specialize in this medium dedicate themselves to preserving this ancient art form while adding their own unique style and interpretation.

Stained glass portraits continue to captivate viewers with their timeless beauty and ability to transform ordinary spaces into extraordinary works of art. The artistry and craftsmanship involved in creating these portraits make them a cherished and enduring form of artistic expression.

items.name: Stanley Donwood Style
items.description:
Stanley Donwood is an English artist and writer known for his collaborations with the rock band Radiohead and his distinctive artwork associated with their album covers and promotional materials. He has played a significant role in shaping the visual identity of the band and has gained recognition for his unique and thought-provoking style.

Donwood's artwork often incorporates elements of dystopia, surrealism, and social commentary. His creations range from intricate pen-and-ink drawings to digital collages and mixed media pieces. He employs a variety of techniques to achieve his desired effects, including layering, texture, and bold use of color.

One of Donwood's most famous collaborations with Radiohead is the cover art for their album "OK Computer," which features a striking image of a heavily distorted highway interchange. The artwork perfectly captures the album's themes of technology, isolation, and modern anxiety.

His other collaborations with the band include album covers for "Kid A," "Amnesiac," and "Hail to the Thief," among others. Donwood's artwork often reflects the introspective and thought-provoking nature of Radiohead's music, complementing the band's sonic explorations with his visual interpretations.

In addition to his work with Radiohead, Donwood has exhibited his artwork in galleries and published several books. His creations often convey a sense of unease and challenge conventional perspectives, inviting viewers to question the status quo and explore the complexities of the modern world.

Stanley Donwood's artistic contributions have left an indelible mark on the music and art scenes. His collaborations with Radiohead and his individual works continue to inspire and captivate audiences, inviting them to delve into the rich and provocative landscapes he creates.

items.name: Stephan Martiniere Style

Stephan Martiniere is a French-born artist and illustrator known for his stunning science fiction and fantasy artwork. With a career spanning over three decades, he has made significant contributions to the entertainment industry, particularly in the fields of film, animation, and video games.

Martiniere's artwork is characterized by its vibrant colors, imaginative settings, and intricate details. He has a remarkable ability to create immersive worlds and bring fantastical creatures and environments to life. His use of light and shadow adds depth and drama to his illustrations, capturing the imagination of viewers.

His talent and versatility have led to collaborations with major studios and companies, including work on films like "Star Wars: Episode II - Attack of the Clones," "Tron: Legacy," and "Guardians of the Galaxy." Martiniere's concept designs and visual development have played a crucial role in shaping the visual aesthetics of these productions.

In addition to his work in the film industry, Martiniere has also illustrated book covers, created concept art for video games, and contributed to magazines and art publications. He has received numerous awards and accolades for his art, including multiple Chesley Awards and Spectrum Fantastic Art Awards.

Martiniere's artwork stands out for its ability to transport viewers to fantastical realms and captivate them with its beauty and imagination. His ability to seamlessly blend science fiction and fantasy elements creates a unique and compelling visual language that has made him a highly regarded artist in his field.

Stephan Martiniere's contributions to the world of art and entertainment have left a lasting impact. His ability to create immersive worlds and awe-inspiring visuals continues to inspire artists and captivate audiences, making him a true visionary in the realm of science fiction and fantasy art.

items.name: Stephen Gammell Style
items.description:
Stephen Gammell is an American artist known for his distinctive and haunting illustrations, particularly in the field of children's literature. His dark and atmospheric artwork has left a lasting impact on readers, evoking a sense of mystery and unease.

Gammell's style is characterized by its use of bold lines, intricate details, and a unique approach to color. His illustrations often depict fantastical creatures, eerie landscapes, and otherworldly scenes. He has a talent for creating a sense of atmosphere and emotion through his art, drawing readers into his imaginative worlds.

One of Gammell's most notable collaborations is with author Alvin Schwartz on the "Scary Stories to Tell in the Dark" series. His illustrations for these books became iconic, leaving a lasting impression on readers of all ages. His ability to capture the essence of horror and the supernatural added an extra layer of depth to the stories, enhancing the overall reading experience.

Gammell's illustrations have been praised for their ability to tap into primal fears and evoke a sense of unease. Despite being primarily associated with horror and dark themes, his artwork also showcases moments of beauty and wonder, demonstrating his range as an artist.

His contributions to the field of children's literature have been recognized with numerous awards, including the Caldecott Medal for his illustration work. Gammell's artwork continues to resonate with readers and has cemented his status as a highly influential illustrator.

Stephen Gammell's unique artistic style and ability to create evocative and unsettling imagery have made him a beloved and iconic figure in children's literature. His illustrations have left an indelible mark, bringing stories to life and igniting the imagination of readers around the world.

items.name: Studio Ghibli Style
items.description:
The Studio Ghibli style refers to the distinctive artistic and storytelling approach seen in the animated films produced by Studio Ghibli. It is characterized by its attention to detail, hand-drawn animation, richly crafted worlds, and emotionally resonant storytelling.

Visually, the Studio Ghibli style often features lush and vibrant environments, meticulously designed backgrounds, and intricate character designs. The attention to detail is remarkable, with carefully rendered textures, naturalistic movements, and expressive facial expressions. The animation captures a sense of fluidity and grace, immersing viewers in a visually stunning cinematic experience.

Storytelling is at the heart of the Studio Ghibli style. The films often explore themes of nature, the environment, coming-of-age, and the power of human connections. They possess a unique ability to blend fantasy elements with grounded, relatable narratives, resulting in stories that are both whimsical and deeply resonant. Studio Ghibli films often celebrate the imagination and the spirit of adventure, while also grappling with deeper philosophical questions and social commentary.

The studio's films also feature strong and complex characters, particularly young protagonists who embark on transformative journeys of self-discovery and personal growth. These characters often face challenges and conflicts that allow for exploration of universal themes such as identity, love, loss, and the duality of human nature.

Music plays an integral role in the Studio Ghibli style, with beautiful and emotive scores composed by Joe Hisaishi. The music enhances the storytelling, evoking a wide range of emotions and further immersing viewers in the enchanting worlds created by the studio.

The Studio Ghibli style has captivated audiences worldwide, transcending language and cultural barriers. The films' artistry, imagination, and universal themes have earned them a devoted following and critical acclaim. The studio's commitment to craftsmanship, creativity, and storytelling continues to inspire both animators and film enthusiasts, leaving a lasting impact on the world of animation.

items.name: Syd Mead Style
items.description:
Syd Mead was an American industrial designer and concept artist known for his visionary work in the fields of science fiction and futurism. His designs and illustrations have had a profound impact on popular culture and have influenced numerous films, video games, and architectural concepts.

Mead's style is characterized by his ability to envision futuristic landscapes, vehicles, and technologies that are both innovative and aesthetically captivating. His designs often feature sleek, streamlined forms, bold use of color, and a meticulous attention to detail. Mead's work combines elements of realism and fantasy, resulting in a unique blend of visionary concepts grounded in practical functionality.

One of Mead's most notable contributions was his concept design work for films such as "Blade Runner," "Tron," and "Aliens." His imaginative creations, ranging from futuristic cityscapes to futuristic vehicles, helped shape the visual identity of these films and influenced the sci-fi genre as a whole.

Beyond film, Mead's influence extended to the fields of architecture, transportation, and product design. His futuristic visions of cities, transportation systems, and everyday objects pushed the boundaries of what was considered possible, inspiring generations of designers and artists.

Mead's impact on popular culture cannot be overstated. His ability to blend artistic creativity with a deep understanding of industrial design principles made him a pioneer in his field. His work continues to captivate audiences, and his legacy lives on as a testament to his unparalleled talent and visionary imagination.

Syd Mead's contributions to the world of design and science fiction have left an indelible mark. His visionary concepts and iconic designs have inspired countless artists, designers, and filmmakers, ensuring that his influence will be felt for generations to come.

items.name: Simone Martini Style
items.description:
Simone Martini (c. 1284-1344) was an Italian painter active during the Gothic period. He was highly regarded for his mastery of the Sienese school of painting and is considered one of the most influential artists of his time.

Martini's style was characterized by its elegance, refinement, and attention to detail. His paintings often featured delicate figures with graceful postures, intricate drapery, and vibrant colors. He had a remarkable ability to capture the subtleties of facial expressions, conveying emotions with great sensitivity.

Martini's subjects ranged from religious and mythological scenes to portraits. His religious paintings often depicted moments from the life of Christ and the Virgin Mary, showcasing a blend of divine spirituality and human tenderness. His use of gold leaf in his artworks added a luminous and ethereal quality to his compositions.

One of Martini's most famous works is the fresco cycle in the Palazzo Pubblico in Siena, depicting scenes from the life of Emperor Charlemagne. These frescoes demonstrate his skill in creating elaborate narrative compositions with rich details.

Martini's influence extended beyond his own time, as his elegant style and refined technique inspired generations of artists. His works were highly sought after, and he received numerous prestigious commissions throughout his career.

Simone Martini's contributions to the Sienese school and the Gothic period are widely recognized. His refined style, attention to detail, and ability to convey emotion continue to captivate viewers and serve as a testament to his artistic skill and creativity.

items.name: Tamara De Lempicka Style
items.description:
Tamara de Lempicka was a Polish Art Deco painter known for her bold and glamorous portraits, which epitomized the elegance and opulence of the 1920s and 1930s. Her distinctive style combined elements of cubism and neoclassicism, resulting in artworks that exuded sensuality, sophistication, and a sense of modernity.

De Lempicka's portraits often featured strong and confident women, depicted with elongated figures, sharp lines, and vibrant colors. Her subjects were often glamorous and seductive, reflecting the spirit of the era. Her use of bold brushstrokes and geometric shapes created a sense of dynamism and energy in her compositions.

While her subject matter primarily focused on portraiture, De Lempicka also explored other themes, including landscapes and still life. Her art captured the essence of the Art Deco movement, characterized by its sleek and stylized aesthetic.

Throughout her career, De Lempicka gained recognition and popularity among the elite and celebrities of the time. Her works were displayed in prestigious exhibitions and galleries, solidifying her status as a prominent artist of the Art Deco era.

Tamara de Lempicka's art continues to captivate audiences with its glamour, elegance, and modernist approach. Her portraits offer a glimpse into the roaring twenties, reflecting the spirit of a transformative era. Her legacy as a pioneering female artist and her significant contributions to the Art Deco movement remain celebrated and influential in the world of art.

items.name: teamLab Style
items.description:
teamLab Style refers to the artistic and technological approach developed by the interdisciplinary art collective teamLab. Known for their immersive and interactive installations, teamLab creates digital art experiences that blur the boundaries between art, technology, and nature.

teamLab Style is characterized by its fusion of digital and physical elements, incorporating cutting-edge technology such as projection mapping, sensors, and interactive displays. Their installations often invite viewer participation, allowing individuals to interact with the artwork and become part of the immersive experience.

The aesthetics of teamLab Style are often marked by vibrant colors, fluid and organic forms, and a sense of ethereal beauty. Their installations explore themes of nature, light, movement, and the interconnectedness of all living beings.

The teamLab Style also emphasizes the importance of collective creativity and collaboration. The collective consists of artists, programmers, engineers, and other specialists who work together to create immersive and transformative art experiences.

teamLab's innovative approach to art and their ability to merge technology, art, and nature has garnered global recognition. Their exhibitions and installations have been showcased in major museums and galleries worldwide, captivating audiences with their mesmerizing and boundary-pushing creations.

In summary, teamLab Style represents the artistic and technological approach developed by the interdisciplinary collective teamLab. It combines digital art, technology, and viewer interaction to create immersive and transformative experiences. With their vibrant aesthetics and emphasis on collaboration, teamLab has established itself as a leading force in the world of digital and interactive art.

items.name: Theodore Robinson Style
items.description:
Theodore Robinson was an American painter and one of the pioneers of American Impressionism. He was a key figure in introducing the Impressionist style to the United States and played a significant role in the development of American art.

Robinson's paintings often depicted landscapes, rural scenes, and figures in outdoor settings. He was particularly drawn to the effects of light and atmosphere, capturing the fleeting qualities of nature with loose brushwork and a keen eye for color. His works showcased the influence of French Impressionism, as he studied and worked alongside renowned artists such as Claude Monet and Pierre-Auguste Renoir in Giverny, France.

Robinson's style was characterized by its sensitivity and delicacy, with a focus on capturing the subtleties of nature and the transient moments of everyday life. His landscapes and genre scenes displayed a harmony between nature and humanity, reflecting the peaceful and idyllic aspects of rural existence.

In addition to his landscape paintings, Robinson also created portraits and still lifes, showing his versatility as an artist. His use of soft colors, gentle brushwork, and an overall sense of tranquility contributed to the overall aesthetic of his work.

Theodore Robinson's contributions to American Impressionism and his dedication to capturing the essence of light and nature have had a lasting impact on the art world. His paintings continue to be celebrated for their beauty, sensitivity, and contribution to the development of American art in the late 19th and early 20th centuries.

items.name: Thomas Cole Style
items.description:
Thomas Cole was an American painter and founder of the Hudson River School, a group of artists known for their romantic and awe-inspiring landscapes. He was a leading figure in the development of American landscape painting and had a profound influence on the American art scene of the 19th century.

Cole's paintings often depicted grand, panoramic views of nature, including mountains, forests, rivers, and valleys. He had a deep appreciation for the beauty and power of the American landscape, and his works aimed to capture the sublime and spiritual qualities of nature.

One of Cole's notable contributions was his ability to infuse his landscapes with a sense of narrative and symbolism. His paintings often told stories or conveyed allegorical messages, exploring themes such as the cycle of life, the fragility of civilization, and the harmony between humanity and the natural world.

Cole's style was characterized by his meticulous attention to detail, rich color palette, and skillful rendering of light and atmosphere. He often employed dramatic lighting effects and carefully composed scenes to create a sense of drama and awe in his landscapes.

Beyond his artistic achievements, Cole was also an advocate for the preservation of natural landscapes. His paintings played a significant role in promoting the idea of conservation and environmental stewardship, inspiring a sense of appreciation and reverence for the American wilderness.

Thomas Cole's legacy as a landscape painter and founder of the Hudson River School continues to resonate today. His evocative and masterful depictions of the American landscape have left an indelible mark on the art world, inspiring generations of artists and fostering a deeper connection between art, nature, and the human spirit.

items.name: SDXL 0.9 Modded Workflows Pack (Designed to Run on 16GB RAM +12GB VRAM 1920x1920)
items.description:
1.1 Update:

-Added more interesting 2 pass PRE upscale algorithm.

-Added LORA\LYCORIS\LOCON etc. loader for 1.5 model.

-You can load and use any 1.x or 2.x models in 1.5 mods.

What you can do:

+Use Original SDXL Workflow to render images.

+Use Modded SDXL where SDXL Refiner works as Img2Img.

+Use SDXL Refiner as Img2Img and feed your pictures.

+Use Modded SDXL where SD1.5 Model works as Refiner.

+Use Modded SDXL where SD1.5 Model works as Base.

+You can load and use any 1.x or 2.x models in 1.5 mods.

+LORA\LYCORIS\LOCON support for 1.5 models in Mods.

+Different Prompt Boxes for Refiner and for Base.

+Disable Base or Refiner models and use just one.

+Change CLIP layer.

+Pre/Post Upscalers.

Main goal of all this workflows is simplicity:

-Minimum nodes and modules (but fully featured).

-Works on 16GB RAM + 12GB VRAM and can render 1920x1920.

-Easy and fast use without extra modules to download.

What you need:

-ComfyUI.

-Pruned SDXL 0.9 Models (Base + Refiner) around 6GB each.

-Close ALL that you don't need in Windows, you need to be around 2GB~.

-Drag and Drop *.json file to ComfyUI window.

About Different Versions:

-Original SDXL - Works as intended, correct CLIP modules with different prompt boxes. Base SDXL model will stop at around 80% of completion (Use TOTAL STEPS and BASE STEPS to control how much noise will go to refiner), left some noise and send it to Refine SDXL Model for completion - this is the way of SDXL.

-Img2Img SDXL Mod - In this workflow SDXL refiner works as a standard img2img model. Base SDXL model will always finish the image as always and saves it, then this image will be sent to refiner, it will add some noise and refine it.

-SD1.5 as Refiner Mod - This will work as Img2Img SDXL Mod, but you can use any 1.5 model as refiner. This is really useful if you want to add some flavor from models you like, also if you are low on RAM or VRAM this is will help you greatly since 1.5 models are small and fast.

-SD1.5 as Base Mod - This will work as Img2Img SDXL Mod, but you can use any 1.5 model as a Base. This is really useful if you want to add some oomph from SDXL refiner for models you like, or just to run some tests.

Tips:

+Don't forget to load VAE for SD1.5 models.

+You can connect and use ESRGAN upscale models (on top) to upscale the end image.

+You can upscale image before refiner kicks in using the R1 two pass upscale module.

+You can connect "Load Image" to R1 and send it to refiner.

+You can disable "For Base" or "For Refiner" loading modules to disable full pipe and not wasting time.

+If you low on RAM or VRAM use "SD1.5 as Refiner Mod" workflow, it is fine.

Here is a cookie for reading all this =D

items.name: Thomas Kinkade Style
items.description:
Thomas Kinkade, also known as the "Painter of Light," was an American artist known for his idyllic and romanticized depictions of landscapes, cottages, and cozy scenes. He gained immense popularity for his paintings, which were often reproduced as prints and widely distributed.

Kinkade's style is characterized by its emphasis on warm, glowing light, vibrant colors, and a sense of tranquility. His paintings often portray serene landscapes, charming cottages, and inviting scenes that evoke a nostalgic and idealized vision of rural life.

Kinkade's artworks have a strong focus on faith, family, and the beauty of nature. Many of his paintings incorporate elements of Christian symbolism and messages of hope, making his art resonate with a wide audience, particularly those seeking comfort and a sense of peace.

While Kinkade's work has garnered a large following and commercial success, it has also been subject to criticism. Some argue that his paintings may lean towards sentimentality and a simplistic view of the world, lacking in artistic depth and innovation. Nonetheless, his ability to tap into the desires of many individuals for a retreat into a simpler, more peaceful existence has made him a prominent figure in the realm of popular art.

Thomas Kinkade's artworks continue to be popular and widely collected, despite the debates surrounding his artistic merit. His legacy lies in his ability to create art that resonates emotionally with viewers, offering a comforting escape into a picturesque world of beauty and tranquility.

Thomas Moran Style
items.description:
Thomas Moran was an American painter and printmaker who played a pivotal role in the development of the Hudson River School, a group of landscape painters known for their romantic and highly detailed portrayals of American landscapes. He is best known for his majestic and awe-inspiring depictions of the American West.

Moran's paintings often showcased vast, panoramic views of natural landscapes, including mountains, canyons, and rivers. He had a deep appreciation for the grandeur and beauty of the American wilderness, and his works aimed to capture the sublime and spiritual qualities of these landscapes.

One of Moran's most famous works is his painting "The Grand Canyon of the Yellowstone," which played a significant role in the establishment of Yellowstone National Park. His ability to convey the breathtaking beauty and unique character of the American West through his art helped foster a sense of appreciation and stewardship for the country's natural treasures.

Moran's style was characterized by his meticulous attention to detail, realistic rendering of light and atmosphere, and his use of vibrant colors. He often depicted the interplay of light and shadow, capturing the dramatic and ever-changing qualities of nature.

In addition to his paintings, Moran also produced etchings and engravings, further showcasing his mastery of various artistic techniques. His works had a profound impact on the art world, influencing subsequent generations of landscape painters and contributing to the popularization of the American West as a subject matter for artistic exploration.

Thomas Moran's legacy as a landscape painter and his contributions to the Hudson River School continue to be celebrated. His ability to capture the sublime beauty of the American West and inspire a sense of awe in viewers remains a testament to his talent and enduring influence on American art.

items.name: Thomas Schaller Style
items.description:
Thomas Schaller is an American watercolor artist known for his architectural and cityscape paintings. He is highly regarded for his ability to capture the essence of a location and convey a sense of mood and atmosphere through his expressive brushwork and use of color.

Schaller's paintings often feature urban scenes, cityscapes, and architectural elements. His work focuses on capturing the interplay of light and shadow, and he skillfully uses watercolor techniques to create dynamic and vibrant compositions. His style is characterized by loose, gestural brushstrokes and a keen sense of abstraction, allowing the viewer to appreciate both the representational aspects of his paintings and their emotive qualities.

In addition to his technical skill, Schaller's art is also distinguished by his unique artistic perspective. He often selects viewpoints and angles that offer a fresh and unconventional take on familiar landmarks, challenging the viewer's perception and inviting them to see the world in a new light.

Schaller is not only an accomplished artist but also a respected instructor, sharing his knowledge and passion for watercolor through workshops and instructional materials. He is highly regarded for his ability to teach and inspire other artists to explore their own creative potential.

Thomas Schaller's work has been exhibited and collected internationally, and his contributions to the watercolor medium have earned him numerous awards and accolades. His paintings continue to captivate viewers with their expressive beauty, evoking a sense of wonder and appreciation for the architectural and urban landscapes that surround us.

items.name: Tim Walker Style
items.description:
Tim Walker is a British fashion photographer known for his whimsical and fantastical style. His photographs are characterized by their dreamlike quality, rich storytelling, and imaginative settings. Walker has gained recognition for his ability to create visually stunning and captivating images that transport viewers to surreal and magical worlds.

Walker's photography often features elaborate sets, extravagant costumes, and theatrical compositions. He draws inspiration from fairy tales, mythology, art history, and literature, infusing his images with a sense of enchantment and wonder. His use of lighting and color adds to the ethereal atmosphere, creating a sense of otherworldliness.

One of Walker's notable trademarks is his collaboration with stylists, designers, and creatives to bring his visions to life. Together, they craft intricate narratives and showcase the artistry and craftsmanship of fashion and design.

Walker's work has graced the pages of renowned fashion magazines and has been exhibited in galleries and museums worldwide. His ability to blend fashion, storytelling, and visual art has made him a highly influential figure in the fashion industry, inspiring both photographers and fashion enthusiasts alike.

Tim Walker's photography challenges conventions and invites viewers into a world of imagination and fantasy. Through his distinctive style, he continues to push the boundaries of fashion photography and create timeless and captivating images that inspire and transport viewers to extraordinary realms.

items.name: Tintoretto Style
items.description:
Tintoretto, whose real name was Jacopo Comin, was an Italian painter during the Renaissance period. He was known for his dramatic and dynamic style, characterized by his use of bold brushwork, intense colors, and theatrical compositions.

Tintoretto's paintings often depicted religious and historical subjects, and he was particularly skilled at creating monumental and highly energetic compositions. His works exude a sense of movement and emotion, capturing the intensity of the human experience and the dramatic narratives of the scenes he portrayed.

One of Tintoretto's notable achievements was his ability to capture the effects of light and shadow. He used chiaroscuro, the contrast between light and dark, to create a sense of depth and dimensionality in his paintings. His mastery of this technique added a sense of drama and realism to his works.

Tintoretto's style also exhibited a sense of experimentation and innovation. He often deviated from traditional compositional norms, incorporating unconventional perspectives and spatial distortions to create a sense of dynamism and visual interest.

His artistic approach and unconventional techniques had a significant influence on later generations of painters, particularly the Baroque movement. Artists such as Peter Paul Rubens and Diego Vel√°zquez were inspired by Tintoretto's expressive brushwork and dramatic compositions.

Tintoretto's legacy as a master painter endures to this day. His works can be found in museums and art collections worldwide, celebrated for their dynamic energy, boldness, and powerful storytelling. His contributions to the art world continue to inspire and captivate audiences, making him a prominent figure in the history of art.

items.name: Todd Hido Style
items.description:
Todd Hido is an American photographer known for his haunting and evocative images, particularly his work in the genre of landscape and domestic photography. He captures scenes that exude a sense of mystery, isolation, and nostalgia, inviting viewers into his atmospheric and often cinematic world.

Hido's photographs often depict ordinary suburban and rural settings, but they possess an eerie and enigmatic quality. He plays with light and shadow, creating a moody and atmospheric ambiance. His use of color and composition adds to the overall sense of quiet introspection and melancholy in his work.

One of Hido's notable series is "House Hunting," in which he explores the concept of home and the psychological implications of domestic spaces. Through his lens, he captures both the intimacy and alienation that can be found within the walls of a home, inviting viewers to contemplate the complex and often hidden aspects of personal life.

Hido's style is characterized by his attention to detail and his ability to evoke a range of emotions through his imagery. His photographs have a sense of narrative and invite viewers to engage with their own interpretations and reflections.

His work has been exhibited internationally and is highly regarded for its atmospheric quality and emotional resonance. Hido's photographs continue to captivate audiences, offering a glimpse into the quiet moments and inner landscapes of the human experience.

Cautions (Must Read)

For anime model,

pls disable 'face restoration' during generating.

pls disable 'face restoration' during generating.

pls disable 'face restoration' during generating.

  • Some preview images are generated using 'Hires Fix' and upscaled using 'SD Upscale'. Thus, if you wanna generate the preview images, pls download the original preview images and analyze them using 'PNG INFO' in webui to get all generating information.

BTW, make sure set this option in 'Stable Diffusion' settings to 'CPU' to successfully regenerate the preview images with the same seed.

______________

There are 4 Versions here. The original Shidoshi Mix and Shidoshi Mix 2. Shidoshi Mix was my original "final". It almost has a flash photography like effect and brighter contrast. Shidoshi Mix 2 was mixing a few more models in and ended up with a little darker feel to it. The other Shidoshi Mix 2's are with baked in loras for detail. The base "Woman" and "Man" look like a mish-mash of every race on the planet leaning towards an Asian look. I find that using something like "Irish Woman" or "English Man" will give white people output. Also using "Asian" in the neg along with "Style Asian Less" embedding created by the great Zovya https://civitai.com/user/Zovya/models , also helps. This model seems to excel at generating Asian people. These models also love generating nudes.

These are a mix of several models I've merged (using "trained difference" and the new elemental merge adjustments) over the last couple of months or so.

The models used:

-And more... I just can't remember which ones I used and I didn't save the metadata into most of the mixed models as I had no intention of sharing.

Personal opinion crap:

Best res: 768x576 (4:3 ratio looks nice) and it can do 1024x768 quite well too. Always use the Hires Fix though (0.2-0.4 denoise?).

I use the DPM++ 2M SDE Karras sampler with higher steps (35-50). A personal preference.

CFG scale: 6-9.5... Gets a little over saturated at 10+. Dynamic thresholding works well though.

If it wont listen to your prompts, flip the Clip Skip to 2 and try it out.

Most Loras, embeddings, and LyCORIS I've tried work well. Can't comment on hypernetworks, as I don't use them.

Irises and pupils get funky at times. Use ADetailer for correction. Usually the Hires Fixes it.

Samples uploaded are without negative embeddings.

But always use the:

NEG PROMPT: (worst quality:1.8), (low quality:1.8), (normal quality:1.8), else it looks like poop.

I usually use the "Add_detail" Lora for the extra kick of realism.

Enjoy.

Please don't use this for commercial use. I didn't train the original checkpoints and therefore I shouldn't have a say on what can be done with this model.

It's kinda like the people who put out the crap remixed music coming out these days, mumbles some crap vocals over top, and then takes credit for being some wonderful artist . If it wasnt for the original checkpoint artists, we wouldn't have remixes.

items.name: Frankenstein (Boris Karloff) Lora
items.description:
Fire bad... lora good!

Be nice, have fun!

Frankenstein's monster or Frankenstein's creature, often erroneously referred to as simply "Frankenstein",[1] is a fictional character who first appeared in Mary Shelley's 1818 novel Frankenstein; or, The Modern Prometheus as the main antagonist. Shelley's title thus compares the monster's creator, Victor Frankenstein, to the mythological character Prometheus, who fashioned humans out of clay and gave them fire.

In Shelley's Gothic story, Victor Frankenstein builds the creature in his laboratory through an ambiguous method based on a scientific principle he discovered. Shelley describes the monster as 8 feet (240¬†cm) tall and emotional. The monster attempts to fit into human society but is shunned, which leads him to seek revenge against Frankenstein. According to the scholar Joseph Carroll, the monster occupies "a border territory between the characteristics that typically define protagonists and antagonists".[2]

Frankenstein's monster became iconic in popular culture, and has been featured in various forms of media, including films, television series, merchandise and video games. The most popularly recognized versions are the film portrayals by Boris Karloff in the 1931 film Frankenstein, the 1935 sequel Bride of Frankenstein, and the 1939 sequel Son of Frankenstein.

items.name: POV Sex From Behind
items.description:
There are two LoRAs included here. They can be used on their own or in combination. One is for a POV reverse cowgirl position, and the other is a general POV from behind.

p0vr3vc0wg1rl is more heavily trained, so expect similar results with each generation. This can sometimes also lead to hairy legs.

p0vfr0mb3h1nd is trained on a much more broad dataset. This leads to it being more versatile, but also can result in some odd results.

POV can be a tricky beast. The legs can often be a bit wonky. The more you describe what you want, the more likely it will be to produce good results.

These prompt inclusions will generally help:

  • rear view (a rear view photo of...)

  • having sex

  • from behind

  • riding a dick

Note: for whatever reason, p0vfr0mb3h1nd doesn't seem to play well with RealisticVision.

Have fun!

All of these are considered for testing only. We were testing Rank Size against VRAM consumption at various batch sizes. Happy to report training on 12GB is possible on lower batches and this seems easier to train with than 2.1-768.

items.name: kt_mix
items.description:
Model intended for generation of anime-style images with a touch of realism and realistic images with a touch of anime influence.

v6.0 is a richer model capable of producing a spectrum of outputs from very anime-style to very realistic.

It is recommended to put "anime" at the end of a prompt for a balanced mix of anime and realism. Adjust the weight of "anime" (e.g. use "(anime:1.5)") to control the level of anime influence on the output. Or, for heavy realism, anime may be omitted from the prompt. See the v6.0 gallery for an example of how to tune the level of anime style / realism.

Using older versions:

Use v3.0 for a slightly more anime-style look.

Use v4.0 for a balanced mix of anime-style and realism.

Use v5.0 for a slightly more realistic look.

See the gallery for each model for some example prompts and results.

modelVersions.name: v6.1

items.name: FoolKat GOD-OF-ANIME
items.description:
Update - 8/6/23 - Version 2 is out! V2 mixes GOD-OF-ANIME with GOD-OF-STORMS to provide an aesthetic that is right in the middle between the comic book style of STORMS and the anime style of V1. If you want pure anime I recommend V1, but for slightly stylized anime, V2 is great! Hope you enjoy.

This is the fourth model in my God series.

You can find all the models at GOD-OF-GREED, GOD-OF-ENVY, GOD-OF-LOVE, GOD-OF-ANIME, GOD-OF-LUST, GOD-OF-JUSTICE, GOD-OF-TIME, GOD-OF-FANTASY, GOD-OF-JOY, GOD-OF-HORROR, GOD-OF-PRIDE, GOD-OF-PUNK, GOD-OF-STORMS, GOD-OF-EUPHORIA, GOD-OF-GLUTTONY, GOD-OF-THE-WEST, GOD-OF-BEAUTY, GOD-OF-SEDUCTION, and GOD-OF-PEACE.

This model is a mix of my FoolKat_GOD-OF-ENVY_V1, Sexy Toons feat. Pipa and Perceptron. The model was actually a first attempt at creating my GOD-OF-LUST model, but the art style I wanted didn't transfer over. However, it does make a great anime model with highly detailed characters and backgrounds.

The model has Blessed2 VAE baked into it, so no VAE required.

All of the images I upload for this model are unedited and don't use any special extensions like ControlNet. I do not do any inpainting or img2img to correct errors. Why? Because you deserve to see how the model works without any touchup or special extensions like ControlNet. You can surely get better images by putting in the extra work, which I do for my personal images. The samples are just meant to showcase what the model can do raw with nothing but prompt engineering.
